        "avatar_template": "/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/c/b5e925/{size}.png",
        "created_at": "2025-03-25T12:57:27.959Z",
        "cooked": "<p>Unlike the Android and iOS clients, the desktop client (macOS at least) doesn’t seem to re-encode videos, at least not all of them. This causes 3 issues:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Metadata isn’t removed. Those receiving the file get the original file (same hash). This is bad for privacy, which matters due to some of Signal’s use cases.</li>\n<li>The receiving user might not be able to watch the video (eg: some iPhones receiving VP9 videos).</li>\n<li>Sometime videos that can be sent from a mobile client can’t be sent from the desktop because the file is “too large”.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>I’ve <a href=\"https://github.com/signalapp/Signal-Desktop/issues/7235\" rel=\"noopener nofollow ugc\">reported this on github</a>, but maybe I wasn’t clear enough and it was interpreted as a feature request… but the iOS/Android clients remove metadata for privacy reasons and compress files… so this is half security/privacy problem and half feature request.</p>\n<p>Re-encoding already happens with images. For example, WebP and AVIF are converted to JPEG, same as on the mobile clients.</p>\n<h1><a name=\"p-264187-how-to-reproduce-1\" class=\"anchor\" href=\"#p-264187-how-to-reproduce-1\" aria-label=\"Heading link\"></a>How to reproduce:</h1>\n<ol start=\"0\">\n<li>Using the desktop app, send a video in a format like VP9/OPUS.</li>\n<li>Check the file that the receiver (or one of your other devices) have received.</li>\n<li>Compare the checksums of both files. They’ll be the same.</li>\n<li>The same VP9 file will play on some platforms (eg: Android) but not on others (iOS, at least devices like the iPhone 13).</li>\n</ol>\n<h1><a name=\"p-264187-what-should-happen-instead-2\" class=\"anchor\" href=\"#p-264187-what-should-happen-instead-2\" aria-label=\"Heading link\"></a>What should happen instead:</h1>\n<p>For privacy, security, and usability reasons, the desktop app should process video files like the mobile apps do.</p>",
